     <physDesc>
      <p>There are also a number of other emendations and additions by the Tremulous Hand of Worcester.</p>
       <handDesc>
       <handNote xml:id="DP1032" scribe="Wulfgeat" corresp="http://www.digipal.eu/digipal/hands/1032/"><p>Ker's scribe 'O'. The scribe Wulfgeat. A round Anglo-Saxon miniscule. A slight lean to the right. Round, unroofed a; a mixture of descending insular long s and tall s; round d with short ascender that usually has a small flick or curve to the upper-right at its tip. Ash is of oe-form, with o always somewhat smaller, sometimes with tall e. e is horned, with a short tongue and a squinting eye. Ascenders of tall letters are wedged, leaning towards forking; thorn is noticeably forked. a is quite rounded in form.</p></handNote>
       <handNote xml:id="EC1032b"><p>An addending and emending hand using a slightly finer pen than the main hand. It overall has a tight, pointy, yet flourishy character. The hand adds alternative glosses for certain forms and inserts additional words. The hand writes d and eth with very tall, willowy ascenders, using a single stroke to cross doubled eths, and uses caroline d as well as bent d. e is unhorned, with a very diagonal middle stroke, and is typically ligatured to the following letter. Characteristically, the hand finishes final e with a long hairstroke as a tongue. The hand usually uses a simple comma-shaped insertion mark when adding new material. The same hand can be seen in other places in Hatton 113, inserting words or added alternatives or glosses.</p></handNote>
      </handDesc>
